a("March 1 Movement Korea","1919-03-01","1919-05-01","Korea",["Revolution","Independence Movement"],"The March 1st Movement of 1919 was a massive Korean independence demonstration against Japanese colonial rule. Over 2 million participated in peaceful protests. Japan's violent suppression killed thousands but galvanized the Korean independence movement.",[["1910","Japan annexes Korea"],["1919-03-01","Declaration of Independence read"],["1919-03","Nationwide protests spread"],["1919","2 million+ participate"],["1919","Japanese suppression kills thousands"],["1919","Provisional Government in Shanghai"]]);
a("April 19 Revolution Korea","1960-04-19","1960-04-26","South Korea",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The April 19 Revolution of 1960 was a student-led uprising that toppled South Korean President Syngman Rhee's authoritarian government. The mass protests against election fraud established the principle of democratic resistance in Korean politics.",[["1960-03-15","Rigged elections"],["1960-04-11","Student's body found"],["1960-04-19","Massive student protests; police fire"],["1960-04-25","Nationwide protests"],["1960-04-26","Rhee resigns"],["1960","Second Republic established"]]);
a("May 18 Gwangju Uprising","1980-05-18","1980-05-27","South Korea",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The Gwangju Uprising of May 1980 was a pro-democracy movement brutally suppressed by the South Korean military. Hundreds were killed when troops opened fire on civilians. The uprising became a cornerstone of Korean democratization.",[["1979-10","Park Chung-hee assassinated"],["1979-12","Chun Doo-hwan's coup"],["1980-05-18","Protests begin in Gwangju"],["1980-05-21","Citizens take up arms"],["1980-05-27","Military retakes city"],["1987","Gwangju inspires June Struggle"]]);
a("June Democracy Movement Korea","1987-06-10","1987-06-29","South Korea",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The June Democracy Movement of 1987 was massive nationwide protests demanding direct presidential elections in South Korea. Over one million participated, forcing the military government to accept democratic reforms and direct elections.",[["1987-01","Student tortured to death"],["1987-06-10","Nationwide protests begin"],["1987-06-18","Tear gas in major cities"],["1987-06-26","Over 1 million march"],["1987-06-29","June 29 Declaration accepts reforms"],["1987-12","First free presidential election"]]);
a("French Revolution of 1848","1848-02-22","1848-06-26","France",["Revolution","Political"],"The French Revolution of 1848 overthrew King Louis Philippe and established the Second Republic. It triggered a wave of revolutions across Europe known as the 'Springtime of Nations,' challenging monarchies from Berlin to Vienna to Budapest.",[["1848-02-22","Protests in Paris"],["1848-02-24","Louis Philippe abdicates"],["1848-02-25","Second Republic declared"],["1848-06","June Days workers' uprising"],["1848-12","Louis-Napoleon elected president"],["1852","Second Empire proclaimed"]]);
a("Taiping Rebellion Start","1851-01-11","1851-01-11","China",["Revolution","Rebellion"],"The Jintian Uprising on January 11, 1851, launched the Taiping Rebellion when Hong Xiuquan raised his banner against the Qing dynasty. The rebellion would become one of history's deadliest conflicts, killing 20-30 million.",[["1843","Hong Xiuquan's visions"],["1847","God Worshippers Society grows"],["1851-01-11","Jintian Uprising"],["1851","Taiping Heavenly Kingdom"],["1853","Nanjing captured"],["1864","Rebellion suppressed"]]);
a("Boxer Rebellion","1899-11-02","1901-09-07","China",["Revolution","Rebellion"],"The Boxer Rebellion (1899-1901) was an anti-foreign, anti-Christian uprising in China supported by the Qing dynasty. An eight-nation alliance intervened, captured Beijing, and imposed the humiliating Boxer Protocol. The rebellion hastened the Qing dynasty's fall.",[["1899","Boxer movement grows"],["1900-06","Boxers besiege foreign legations in Beijing"],["1900-08","Eight-Nation Alliance captures Beijing"],["1900","Empress Cixi flees"],["1901-09-07","Boxer Protocol signed"],["1911","Qing dynasty falls"]]);
a("Xinhai Revolution","1911-10-10","1912-02-12","China",["Revolution","Political"],"The Xinhai Revolution of 1911 overthrew the Qing dynasty, ending over 2,000 years of imperial rule in China. Sun Yat-sen became the first president of the Republic of China. The revolution established Asia's first republic.",[["1905","Tongmenghui founded by Sun Yat-sen"],["1911-10-10","Wuchang Uprising"],["1911","Provinces declare independence"],["1912-01-01","Republic of China proclaimed"],["1912-02-12","Emperor Puyi abdicates"],["1912","2,000 years of empire ends"]]);
a("October Revolution Russia","1917-10-25","1917-10-26","Russia",["Revolution","Communist"],"The October Revolution on October 25-26, 1917, saw the Bolsheviks seize power in Petrograd. Lenin's Red Guards stormed the Winter Palace, overthrowing the Provisional Government and establishing the world's first communist state.",[["1917-10-25","Bolsheviks seize key buildings"],["1917-10-26","Winter Palace stormed"],["1917-10-26","Provisional Government arrested"],["1917","Lenin declares Soviet power"],["1918","Russian Civil War begins"],["1922","USSR established"]]);
a("Cuban Revolution","1953-07-26","1959-01-01","Cuba",["Revolution","Political"],"The Cuban Revolution (1953-1959) overthrew dictator Batista and brought Fidel Castro to power. The revolution transformed Cuba into a communist state and became a flashpoint of the Cold War, culminating in the Bay of Pigs and Missile Crisis.",[["1953-07-26","Moncada Barracks attack"],["1956","Castro returns on Granma"],["1957","Sierra Maestra guerrilla campaign"],["1958","Batista's army crumbles"],["1959-01-01","Batista flees; Castro enters Havana"],["1961","Bay of Pigs invasion"]]);
a("Arab Spring Tunisia","2010-12-17","2011-01-14","Tunisia",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The Tunisian Revolution (2010-11) sparked the Arab Spring when Mohamed Bouazizi's self-immolation triggered mass protests against President Ben Ali's authoritarian rule. Ben Ali fled after 23 years in power, inspiring uprisings across the Arab world.",[["2010-12-17","Bouazizi sets himself on fire"],["2010-12","Protests spread across Tunisia"],["2011-01-14","Ben Ali flees to Saudi Arabia"],["2011","New constitution drafted"],["2014","Free elections held"],["2010-11","Arab Spring begins"]]);
a("Egyptian Revolution 2011","2011-01-25","2011-02-11","Egypt",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The Egyptian Revolution of 2011 ousted President Hosni Mubarak after 30 years in power. Millions gathered in Tahrir Square demanding freedom and dignity. The military forced Mubarak's resignation, though the democratic transition was later reversed.",[["2011-01-25","Day of Revolt begins"],["2011-01-28","Friday of Rage"],["2011-02","Tahrir Square occupation"],["2011-02-11","Mubarak resigns"],["2012","Morsi elected president"],["2013","Military coup; Sisi takes power"]]);
a("Velvet Revolution Czechoslovakia","1989-11-17","1989-12-29","Czechoslovakia",["Revolution","Political"],"The Velvet Revolution (1989) peacefully ended communist rule in Czechoslovakia. Student protests sparked mass demonstrations, and playwright Václav Havel became president. The non-violent transition became a model for democratic change.",[["1989-11-17","Student protest brutally suppressed"],["1989-11-20","Mass demonstrations begin"],["1989-11-24","Communist leadership resigns"],["1989-12-29","Havel elected president"],["1989","Communist party loses power"],["1993","Velvet Divorce; Czech and Slovak Republics"]]);
a("Romanian Revolution","1989-12-16","1989-12-25","Romania",["Revolution","Political"],"The Romanian Revolution of 1989 was the only violent overthrow of a communist government in Eastern Europe. Dictator Nicolae Ceaușescu and his wife were executed on Christmas Day after a brief trial. Over 1,000 people died in the uprising.",[["1989-12-16","Protests begin in Timișoara"],["1989-12-21","Ceaușescu rally in Bucharest turns against him"],["1989-12-22","Ceaușescu flees by helicopter"],["1989-12-25","Ceaușescu executed"],["1989","Over 1,000 killed"],["1990","Free elections held"]]);
a("Portuguese Carnation Revolution","1974-04-25","1974-04-25","Portugal",["Revolution","Political"],"The Carnation Revolution on April 25, 1974, was a military coup that ended 48 years of dictatorship in Portugal. Soldiers placed carnations in their gun barrels as a symbol of peace. It led to democracy and the end of Portugal's colonial wars.",[["1926","Dictatorship begins"],["1961","Colonial wars begin"],["1974-04-25","Military coup"],["1974-04-25","Carnations in gun barrels"],["1974","Dictatorship ends"],["1975","Colonial independence granted"]]);
a("English Civil War","1642-08-22","1651-09-03","England",["Revolution","Civil War"],"The English Civil War (1642-1651) between Parliamentarians and Royalists led to King Charles I's execution and Oliver Cromwell's Commonwealth. It established the precedent that no monarch rules without Parliament's consent.",[["1642-08-22","King raises standard at Nottingham"],["1644","Battle of Marston Moor"],["1645","New Model Army; Battle of Naseby"],["1649-01-30","Charles I executed"],["1649","Commonwealth declared"],["1660","Monarchy restored"]]);
a("Meiji Restoration","1868-01-03","1868-01-03","Japan",["Revolution","Political"],"The Meiji Restoration of 1868 ended the Tokugawa shogunate and restored imperial rule under Emperor Meiji. It launched Japan's rapid modernization and industrialization, transforming it from a feudal society into an industrial power within decades.",[["1853","Perry opens Japan"],["1867","Last shogun resigns"],["1868-01-03","Imperial restoration declared"],["1868","Boshin War"],["1871","Feudal domains abolished"],["1889","Meiji Constitution"]]);
a("Peasants War Germany","1524-06-01","1525-05-15","Holy Roman Empire",["Revolution","Rebellion"],"The German Peasants' War (1524-25) was the largest popular uprising in European history before the French Revolution. Inspired partly by Martin Luther's ideas, peasants demanded social and economic reforms. The revolt was brutally crushed, killing up to 100,000.",[["1517","Lutheran Reformation begins"],["1524","Peasant revolts spread"],["1525","Twelve Articles of demands"],["1525","Luther condemns revolt"],["1525-05","Rebellion crushed at Frankenhausen"],["1525","Up to 100,000 killed"]]);
a("Hungarian Revolution 1956","1956-10-23","1956-11-10","Hungary",["Revolution","Anti-Communist"],"The Hungarian Revolution of 1956 was a nationwide revolt against Soviet-imposed communist rule. After initial success, Soviet tanks crushed the uprising, killing 2,500 Hungarians. 200,000 fled as refugees. It demonstrated the limits of Cold War freedom.",[["1956-10-23","Student protests begin"],["1956-10-24","Soviet tanks enter Budapest"],["1956-10-28","Ceasefire; Nagy forms government"],["1956-11-01","Hungary leaves Warsaw Pact"],["1956-11-04","Massive Soviet invasion"],["1956-11-10","Resistance crushed"]]);
a("Prague Spring","1968-01-05","1968-08-21","Czechoslovakia",["Revolution","Reform Movement"],"The Prague Spring of 1968 was an attempt to liberalize communist Czechoslovakia under Alexander Dubček's 'socialism with a human face.' Soviet and Warsaw Pact forces invaded in August, crushing the reforms and establishing the Brezhnev Doctrine.",[["1968-01-05","Dubček becomes party leader"],["1968-04","Action Programme of reforms"],["1968-06","Censorship abolished"],["1968-08-20","Warsaw Pact invasion"],["1968-08-21","500,000 troops occupy country"],["1969","Dubček removed; 'normalization'"]]);
a("Bolshevik Revolution","1917-11-07","1917-11-08","Russia",["Revolution","Communist"],"The Bolshevik Revolution of November 7-8, 1917 (October 25-26 Old Style), saw Lenin's Bolsheviks seize power in Petrograd. The storming of the Winter Palace overthrew the Provisional Government and established the first communist state.",[["1917-11-07","Bolsheviks seize key buildings"],["1917-11-07","Cruiser Aurora fires blank"],["1917-11-08","Winter Palace falls"],["1917","Soviet power declared"],["1918","Civil War begins"],["1922","USSR formed"]]);
a("Candlelight Revolution Korea","2016-10-29","2017-03-10","South Korea",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The Candlelight Revolution (2016-17) was a series of massive peaceful protests demanding President Park Geun-hye's removal over corruption scandals. Up to 1.7 million gathered weekly, leading to Park's impeachment—the first of a sitting president in Korean history.",[["2016-10","Corruption scandal breaks"],["2016-10-29","First candlelight rally"],["2016-12","National Assembly votes impeachment"],["2017-03-10","Constitutional Court upholds"],["2017-05","New president elected"],["2017","Democracy reaffirmed"]]);
a("Revolutions of 1848","1848-02-22","1849-08-28","Europe",["Revolution","Political"],"The Revolutions of 1848 were a wave of political upheavals across Europe, the 'Springtime of Nations.' Revolts in France, Germany, Austria, Hungary, and Italy demanded liberal reforms and national independence. Most were suppressed but planted seeds of future change.",[["1848-02","French revolution topples king"],["1848-03","Revolts in Vienna, Berlin, Milan"],["1848-03","Metternich flees Vienna"],["1848-06","Prague Slav Congress"],["1848-12","Louis-Napoleon elected in France"],["1849","Most revolts suppressed"]]);
a("Jacobite Rising 1745","1745-08-19","1746-04-16","Scotland",["Revolution","Rebellion"],"The Jacobite Rising of 1745, led by Bonnie Prince Charlie, was the last serious attempt to restore the Stuart dynasty to the British throne. After initial success reaching Derby, the Highland army was destroyed at the Battle of Culloden in 1746.",[["1745-08-19","Charles lands in Scotland"],["1745-09","Edinburgh captured"],["1745-12","March reaches Derby"],["1746-01","Retreat to Scotland"],["1746-04-16","Battle of Culloden"],["1746","Highland culture suppressed"]]);
a("Sepoy Mutiny","1857-05-10","1858-06-20","India",["Revolution","Rebellion"],"The Indian Rebellion of 1857, also known as the Sepoy Mutiny, was a major uprising against British East India Company rule. Though eventually suppressed, it led to the dissolution of the Company and direct British Crown rule over India.",[["1857-05-10","Sepoys revolt at Meerut"],["1857-06","Siege of Delhi"],["1857-06","Siege of Lucknow"],["1857-09","Delhi recaptured"],["1858","Rebellion suppressed"],["1858","British Crown takes control"]]);
a("Easter Rising","1916-04-24","1916-04-30","Ireland",["Revolution","Independence"],"The Easter Rising of 1916 was an Irish republican insurrection against British rule in Dublin. Though militarily unsuccessful, the execution of its leaders transformed public opinion and catalyzed the Irish independence movement.",[["1916-04-24","Proclamation of Republic read"],["1916-04-24","GPO seized as headquarters"],["1916-04-29","British reinforcements arrive"],["1916-04-30","Rebels surrender"],["1916-05","15 leaders executed"],["1921","Irish independence achieved"]]);
a("Russian Revolution of 1905","1905-01-22","1905-10-30","Russia",["Revolution","Political"],"The Russian Revolution of 1905 began with Bloody Sunday when troops fired on peaceful petitioners. The ensuing strikes and uprisings forced Tsar Nicholas II to create the Duma and issue the October Manifesto, granting limited constitutional rights.",[["1905-01-22","Bloody Sunday massacre"],["1905-06","Potemkin mutiny"],["1905-10","General strike paralyzes Russia"],["1905-10-30","October Manifesto issued"],["1906","First Duma meets"],["1917","1905 as prelude to 1917"]]);
a("Paris Commune","1871-03-18","1871-05-28","France",["Revolution","Political"],"The Paris Commune of 1871 was a radical socialist government that briefly ruled Paris for 72 days. Established after France's defeat in the Franco-Prussian War, it was brutally suppressed during 'Bloody Week,' killing up to 20,000 Communards.",[["1870","Franco-Prussian War; Paris besieged"],["1871-03-18","Commune proclaimed"],["1871-03","Radical reforms enacted"],["1871-05-21","Bloody Week begins"],["1871-05-28","Commune falls; mass executions"],["1871","Marx analyzes as first workers' state"]]);
a("Fall of the Berlin Wall","1989-11-09","1989-11-09","Germany",["Revolution","Political"],"The Fall of the Berlin Wall on November 9, 1989, was a pivotal event in the Cold War's end. East German authorities opened the border checkpoints after weeks of peaceful protests, and jubilant crowds tore down the wall. It symbolized the end of communist rule in Europe.",[["1961","Berlin Wall built"],["1989-09","Mass protests in Leipzig"],["1989-10","Honecker resigns"],["1989-11-09","Border opened"],["1989-11-09","Wall torn down"],["1990-10-03","German reunification"]]);
a("Storming of the Bastille","1789-07-14","1789-07-14","France",["Revolution","Political"],"The Storming of the Bastille on July 14, 1789, was the symbolic beginning of the French Revolution. A Parisian mob attacked the royal fortress-prison seeking weapons and ammunition. The fall of the Bastille symbolized the end of royal tyranny and is celebrated as France's national day.",[["1789-05","Estates-General meets"],["1789-06-20","Tennis Court Oath"],["1789-07-11","Necker dismissed"],["1789-07-14","Bastille stormed"],["1789-07-14","Governor de Launay killed"],["1789-08","Declaration of Rights of Man"]]);
a("Solidarity Movement Poland","1980-08-14","1989-06-04","Poland",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The Solidarity Movement (1980-1989) was the first independent trade union in a Soviet-bloc country. Led by Lech Wałęsa, it grew into a broad anti-communist movement. After martial law and underground resistance, Solidarity won free elections in 1989.",[["1980-08","Gdańsk shipyard strike"],["1980-09","Solidarity union formed"],["1981-12","Martial law declared"],["1983","Wałęsa wins Nobel Peace Prize"],["1989-06-04","Solidarity wins elections"],["1989","Communist rule ends in Poland"]]);
a("Tiananmen Square Protests","1989-04-15","1989-06-04","China",["Revolution","Democratic Movement"],"The Tiananmen Square protests of 1989 were student-led demonstrations for political reform in Beijing. On June 4, the Chinese military violently cleared the square, killing hundreds to thousands. The 'Tank Man' image became an iconic symbol of resistance.",[["1989-04-15","Hu Yaobang dies; protests begin"],["1989-05","Students occupy Tiananmen Square"],["1989-05-20","Martial law declared"],["1989-06-04","Military clears square"],["1989-06-05","Tank Man confrontation"],["1989","Reforms halted; crackdown continues"]]);

// ============ DISCOVERIES & EXPLORATIONS (~200) ============
a("Columbus Reaches Americas","1492-10-12","1492-10-12","Caribbean",["Discovery","Exploration"],"On October 12, 1492, Christopher Columbus reached the Bahamas, initiating sustained European contact with the Americas. Though he believed he reached Asia, the voyage opened the New World to European exploration, colonization, and the Columbian Exchange.",[["1492-08-03","Ships depart Spain"],["1492-10-12","Land sighted in Bahamas"],["1492","San Salvador, Cuba, Hispaniola visited"],["1493","Columbus returns to Spain"],["1493","Second voyage begins"],["1504","Columbus's fourth and final voyage"]]);
a("Magellan Circumnavigation","1519-09-20","1522-09-06","Global",["Discovery","Exploration"],"The Magellan-Elcano expedition (1519-1522) was the first circumnavigation of the globe. Though Magellan was killed in the Philippines, Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage. It proved the Earth's roundness and the vastness of the Pacific Ocean.",[["1519-09-20","Five ships depart Spain"],["1520","Strait of Magellan crossed"],["1521-03-16","Philippines reached"],["1521-04-27","Magellan killed in battle"],["1522-09-06","Victoria returns to Spain"],["1522","First circumnavigation complete"]]);
a("Apollo 11 Moon Landing","1969-07-20","1969-07-20","United States",["Discovery","Space Exploration"],"On July 20, 1969, Apollo 11 astronaut Neil Armstrong became the first human to walk on the Moon. His words 'That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind' defined the achievement. The mission fulfilled President Kennedy's goal and remains humanity's greatest exploration feat.",[["1961","Kennedy's Moon goal speech"],["1967","Apollo 1 fire kills three"],["1968","Apollo 8 orbits Moon"],["1969-07-16","Apollo 11 launches"],["1969-07-20","Armstrong walks on Moon"],["1972","Apollo 17: last Moon mission"]]);
a("Suez Canal Opening","1869-11-17","1869-11-17","Egypt",["Discovery","Engineering"],"The Suez Canal, opened November 17, 1869, connected the Mediterranean and Red Seas, eliminating the need to sail around Africa. The 193-km waterway transformed global trade and became one of the world's most strategically important chokepoints.",[["1858","Suez Canal Company formed"],["1859","Construction begins"],["1869-11-17","Canal officially opened"],["1875","Britain buys Egypt's shares"],["1956","Suez Crisis"],["2021","Ever Given blocks canal"]]);
a("Panama Canal Opening","1914-08-15","1914-08-15","Panama",["Discovery","Engineering"],"The Panama Canal, opened August 15, 1914, connected the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans through Central America. One of the greatest engineering achievements, it shortened the New York-San Francisco sea route by 8,000 miles.",[["1881","French attempt fails"],["1904","US takes over construction"],["1907","Workers battle disease and terrain"],["1914-08-15","Canal officially opens"],["1977","Carter-Torrijos Treaties"],["1999","Panama assumes control"]]);
a("Vasco da Gama Reaches India","1498-05-20","1498-05-20","India",["Discovery","Exploration"],"Vasco da Gama reached Calicut, India on May 20, 1498, establishing the first direct sea route from Europe to Asia. The voyage opened the lucrative spice trade to Portugal and began the era of European maritime empires in Asia.",[["1497-07-08","Fleet departs Lisbon"],["1497-11","Rounds Cape of Good Hope"],["1498-05-20","Reaches Calicut, India"],["1498","Spice trade established"],["1499","Da Gama returns to Lisbon"],["1510","Portugal captures Goa"]]);
a("Discovery of DNA Structure","1953-04-25","1953-04-25","United Kingdom",["Discovery","Science"],"On April 25, 1953, James Watson and Francis Crick published the double helix structure of DNA in Nature magazine. Building on Rosalind Franklin's X-ray crystallography, the discovery revealed the mechanism of genetic inheritance and launched modern molecular biology.",[["1869","DNA first isolated by Miescher"],["1944","DNA identified as genetic material"],["1952","Franklin's Photo 51"],["1953-04-25","Double helix published in Nature"],["1962","Nobel Prize to Watson, Crick, Wilkins"],["2003","Human Genome Project completed"]]);
a("Gutenberg Printing Press","1440-01-01","1440-01-01","Germany",["Discovery","Technology"],"Johannes Gutenberg's invention of the movable type printing press around 1440 revolutionized information dissemination. The Gutenberg Bible (1455) was the first major book printed with movable type. The printing press enabled the Reformation, Scientific Revolution, and spread of literacy.",[["1440","Gutenberg develops movable type"],["1450","Printing workshop in Mainz"],["1455","Gutenberg Bible printed"],["1517","Luther's theses printed widely"],["1500","20 million volumes printed in Europe"],["1440","Information revolution begins"]]);
a("Wright Brothers First Flight","1903-12-17","1903-12-17","United States",["Discovery","Aviation"],"On December 17, 1903, Wilbur and Orville Wright made the first sustained, controlled, powered heavier-than-air flight at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina. The longest flight lasted 59 seconds over 852 feet. Their achievement launched the age of aviation.",[["1899","Wright brothers begin research"],["1900","Glider experiments at Kitty Hawk"],["1903-12-17","First powered flight: 12 seconds"],["1903-12-17","Fourth flight: 59 seconds, 852 feet"],["1905","First practical airplane"],["1909","Military contracts"]]);
a("Penicillin Discovery","1928-09-28","1928-09-28","United Kingdom",["Discovery","Medicine"],"Alexander Fleming's accidental discovery of penicillin on September 28, 1928, launched the antibiotic era. Mass production during WWII saved millions of lives. Penicillin is considered one of the most important medical discoveries in history.",[["1928-09-28","Fleming notices mold killing bacteria"],["1929","Fleming publishes findings"],["1940","Florey and Chain develop for clinical use"],["1941","First patient treated"],["1943","Mass production for WWII"],["1945","Nobel Prize to Fleming, Florey, Chain"]]);
a("Discovery of the Americas by Norse","1000-01-01","1000-01-01","North America",["Discovery","Exploration"],"Around 1000 AD, Norse explorer Leif Erikson reached North America, establishing a settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows in Newfoundland. This was the first known European contact with the Americas, nearly 500 years before Columbus.",[["985","Erik the Red colonizes Greenland"],["1000","Leif Erikson sails west"],["1000","Vinland discovered"],["1000","Settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows"],["1014","Norse abandon Vinland"],["1960","Archaeological site confirmed"]]);
a("Darwin Voyage of the Beagle","1831-12-27","1836-10-02","Global",["Discovery","Science"],"Charles Darwin's voyage on HMS Beagle (1831-1836) provided observations that led to his theory of evolution by natural selection. His studies of Galápagos finches and other species revolutionized biology and our understanding of life.",[["1831-12-27","Beagle departs England"],["1832","South American observations"],["1835","Galápagos Islands visited"],["1836-10-02","Returns to England"],["1859","On the Origin of Species published"],["1859","Theory of evolution"]]);
a("First Telegraph Message","1844-05-24","1844-05-24","United States",["Discovery","Technology"],"On May 24, 1844, Samuel Morse sent the first telegraph message 'What hath God wrought' from Washington to Baltimore. The telegraph revolutionized long-distance communication, enabling instant messaging across continents and transforming commerce, journalism, and diplomacy.",[["1837","Morse develops telegraph"],["1838","Morse code created"],["1844-05-24","'What hath God wrought' sent"],["1858","Transatlantic cable attempted"],["1866","Permanent transatlantic cable"],["1876","Telephone supersedes"]]);
a("First Transatlantic Flight","1927-05-20","1927-05-21","Atlantic Ocean",["Discovery","Aviation"],"Charles Lindbergh's solo transatlantic flight from New York to Paris on May 20-21, 1927, in the Spirit of St. Louis made him an international hero. The 33.5-hour flight demonstrated aviation's potential for long-distance travel.",[["1919","Alcock and Brown first Atlantic crossing"],["1927-05-20","Lindbergh departs New York"],["1927-05-21","Lands in Paris after 33.5 hours"],["1927","World celebrates"],["1927","Aviation investment surges"],["1937","Amelia Earhart disappears"]]);
a("Sputnik Launch","1957-10-04","1957-10-04","Soviet Union",["Discovery","Space Exploration"],"Sputnik 1, launched October 4, 1957, was the first artificial satellite to orbit Earth. The Soviet achievement shocked the West, triggering the Space Race and leading to the creation of NASA. Its beeping signal was heard around the world.",[["1957-10-04","Sputnik launched on R-7 rocket"],["1957","84 kg satellite orbits Earth"],["1957","Signal detected worldwide"],["1958","NASA created in response"],["1958","US launches Explorer 1"],["1961","Gagarin first in space"]]);
a("First Human in Space","1961-04-12","1961-04-12","Soviet Union",["Discovery","Space Exploration"],"On April 12, 1961, Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin became the first human in space, orbiting Earth once in Vostok 1. The 108-minute flight was a triumph of Soviet technology and intensified the Space Race.",[["1957","Sputnik launches Space Race"],["1961-04-12","Gagarin orbits Earth"],["1961","108-minute flight"],["1961","Gagarin becomes world hero"],["1961-05","Kennedy announces Moon goal"],["1969","Armstrong walks on Moon"]]);
a("Hubble Space Telescope Launch","1990-04-24","1990-04-24","Earth Orbit",["Discovery","Space Exploration"],"The Hubble Space Telescope, launched April 24, 1990, revolutionized astronomy with its deep-space observations. After a flawed mirror was corrected, Hubble produced stunning images and helped determine the universe's age and expansion rate.",[["1990-04-24","Hubble launched by shuttle Discovery"],["1990","Flawed primary mirror discovered"],["1993","Corrective optics installed"],["1995","Hubble Deep Field image"],["1998","Accelerating expansion discovered"],["2021","James Webb Telescope launched"]]);
a("Invention of the Telephone","1876-03-10","1876-03-10","United States",["Discovery","Technology"],"Alexander Graham Bell made the first telephone call on March 10, 1876, saying 'Mr. Watson, come here. I want to see you.' The invention revolutionized human communication and spawned the telecommunications industry.",[["1874","Bell begins telephone research"],["1876-02-14","Patent filed"],["1876-03-10","First successful call"],["1877","Bell Telephone Company founded"],["1915","First transcontinental call"],["2024","5 billion mobile users"]]);
a("Discovery of X-Rays","1895-11-08","1895-11-08","Germany",["Discovery","Science"],"Wilhelm Röntgen's discovery of X-rays on November 8, 1895, revolutionized medicine by allowing doctors to see inside the human body. The first X-ray image of his wife's hand amazed the world. Röntgen received the first Nobel Prize in Physics.",[["1895-11-08","Röntgen discovers unknown rays"],["1895-12","First X-ray of wife's hand"],["1896","Medical applications begin"],["1896","X-rays used in warfare"],["1901","First Nobel Prize in Physics"],["2024","Essential medical tool"]]);
a("First Radio Broadcast","1920-11-02","1920-11-02","United States",["Discovery","Technology"],"KDKA in Pittsburgh made the first commercial radio broadcast on November 2, 1920, reporting the Harding-Cox presidential election results. Radio broadcasting quickly became a mass medium that transformed entertainment, news, and communication.",[["1895","Marconi pioneers wireless"],["1906","First voice transmission"],["1920-11-02","KDKA broadcasts election results"],["1922","BBC established"],["1930s","Radio's golden age"],["1950s","Television surpasses radio"]]);
a("First Television Broadcast","1928-09-11","1928-09-11","United States",["Discovery","Technology"],"The first television broadcast occurred in 1928 when GE's experimental station W2XB transmitted an image. John Logie Baird and Philo Farnsworth pioneered television technology that would become the dominant entertainment and information medium of the 20th century.",[["1925","Baird demonstrates mechanical TV"],["1927","Farnsworth transmits electronic image"],["1928","GE broadcasts experimental program"],["1936","BBC begins regular broadcasts"],["1941","US commercial broadcasting begins"],["1969","Moon landing watched by 600 million"]]);
a("ARPANET First Message","1969-10-29","1969-10-29","United States",["Discovery","Technology"],"On October 29, 1969, the first ARPANET message was sent between UCLA and Stanford, marking the birth of the internet. The system crashed after transmitting only 'LO' (attempting 'LOGIN'), but it launched the communications revolution.",[["1962","Concept of packet switching"],["1969-10-29","First ARPANET message"],["1971","Email invented"],["1983","TCP/IP adopted"],["1991","World Wide Web launched"],["2024","5+ billion internet users"]]);
a("Completion of Transcontinental Railroad","1869-05-10","1869-05-10","United States",["Discovery","Engineering"],"The First Transcontinental Railroad was completed on May 10, 1869, when the Central Pacific and Union Pacific met at Promontory Summit, Utah. The 'golden spike' ceremony symbolized the unification of a continent. The railroad transformed American commerce and westward expansion.",[["1862","Pacific Railroad Acts signed"],["1863","Construction begins from both ends"],["1866","Chinese laborers blast through Sierra Nevada"],["1869-05-10","Golden spike ceremony"],["1869","Coast-to-coast travel: 6 days vs 6 months"],["1869","Transformation of American West"]]);
a("Splitting of the Atom","1932-04-14","1932-04-14","United Kingdom",["Discovery","Physics"],"John Cockcroft and Ernest Walton first split the atom on April 14, 1932, at Cambridge University. They accelerated protons to break apart lithium nuclei, confirming Einstein's mass-energy equivalence. The achievement opened the door to nuclear energy and weapons.",[["1905","Einstein's E=mc²"],["1911","Rutherford discovers nucleus"],["1932-04-14","Atom split at Cambridge"],["1938","Nuclear fission discovered"],["1942","First nuclear reactor"],["1945","Atomic bombs"]]);
a("Discovery of Gravity","1687-07-05","1687-07-05","England",["Discovery","Physics"],"Isaac Newton published Principia Mathematica on July 5, 1687, presenting his law of universal gravitation. The work described the motion of planets, tides, and falling objects through mathematical laws, establishing the foundation of classical physics.",[["1666","Apple tree legend"],["1684","Halley encourages Newton to write"],["1687-07-05","Principia published"],["1687","Laws of motion described"],["1687","Universal gravitation"],["1905","Einstein modifies with relativity"]]);
a("Completion of Human Genome Project","2003-04-14","2003-04-14","Global",["Discovery","Genetics"],"The Human Genome Project was completed on April 14, 2003, mapping all 3 billion base pairs of human DNA. The 13-year international effort revolutionized medicine, enabling personalized treatments and advancing our understanding of genetic diseases.",[["1990","Project launched"],["1998","Competition from Celera Genomics"],["2000","Working draft announced"],["2003-04-14","Full sequence completed"],["2003","3 billion base pairs mapped"],["2024","Genomic medicine era"]]);
a("Discovery of Electricity","1752-06-15","1752-06-15","United States",["Discovery","Physics"],"Benjamin Franklin's famous kite experiment in June 1752 proved that lightning was electrical. Though not the discoverer of electricity itself, Franklin's work laid the groundwork for understanding electrical phenomena and led to the invention of the lightning rod.",[["1600","William Gilbert coins 'electricity'"],["1745","Leyden jar stores charge"],["1752-06","Franklin's kite experiment"],["1752","Lightning rod invented"],["1800","Volta invents battery"],["1879","Edison's light bulb"]]);
a("First Atomic Bomb Test Trinity","1945-07-16","1945-07-16","United States",["Discovery","Nuclear Physics"],"The Trinity test on July 16, 1945, was the first detonation of a nuclear weapon, in the New Mexico desert. J. Robert Oppenheimer quoted the Bhagavad Gita: 'Now I am become Death, the destroyer of worlds.' Three weeks later, atomic bombs destroyed Hiroshima and Nagasaki.",[["1942","Manhattan Project begins"],["1943","Los Alamos laboratory"],["1945-07-16","Trinity test detonation"],["1945-07-16","Oppenheimer quotes Gita"],["1945-08-06","Hiroshima"],["1945-08-09","Nagasaki"]]);
a("Voyager 1 Launch","1977-09-05","1977-09-05","United States",["Discovery","Space Exploration"],"Voyager 1, launched September 5, 1977, is the most distant human-made object. It explored Jupiter and Saturn before heading to interstellar space, which it entered in 2012. It carries the Golden Record with sounds and images of Earth.",[["1977-09-05","Voyager 1 launched"],["1979","Jupiter flyby"],["1980","Saturn flyby"],["1990","Pale Blue Dot photo"],["2012","Enters interstellar space"],["2024","Still transmitting from 24 billion km"]]);
a("Mars Curiosity Rover Landing","2012-08-06","2012-08-06","Mars",["Discovery","Space Exploration"],"NASA's Curiosity rover landed on Mars on August 6, 2012, using the innovative 'sky crane' system. The car-sized rover has been exploring Gale Crater, finding evidence that Mars once had conditions suitable for microbial life.",[["2011-11-26","Curiosity launches"],["2012-08-06","'Seven minutes of terror' landing"],["2012","Sky crane system succeeds"],["2013","Evidence of habitable environment"],["2014","Organic molecules detected"],["2024","Still operating on Mars"]]);

// ============ DISASTERS & EPIDEMICS (~150) ============
a("Black Death","1347-10-01","1353-01-01","Europe",["Disaster","Pandemic"],"The Black Death (1347-1353) was the deadliest pandemic in human history, killing an estimated 75-200 million people—roughly one-third of Europe's population. The bubonic plague devastated societies, caused labor shortages that ended feudalism, and profoundly transformed European civilization.",[["1346","Plague arrives at Crimean ports"],["1347","Ships bring plague to Sicily"],["1348","Plague ravages Italy, France, Spain"],["1349","England, Germany affected"],["1350","Scandinavia reached"],["1353","Worst phase ends"]]);
a("Spanish Flu Pandemic","1918-03-01","1920-04-01","Global",["Disaster","Pandemic"],"The Spanish Flu of 1918-1920 infected one-third of the world's population and killed 50-100 million people. It struck in three waves, with the second being the deadliest. The pandemic killed more people than World War I and disproportionately affected young adults.",[["1918-03","First cases reported at Fort Riley, Kansas"],["1918-04","Virus spreads with WWI troop movements"],["1918-09","Deadly second wave begins"],["1918-10","Peak mortality month"],["1919","Third wave"],["1920","Pandemic subsides"]]);
a("COVID-19 Pandemic","2019-12-01","2023-05-05","Global",["Disaster","Pandemic"],"The COVID-19 pandemic, caused by SARS-CoV-2, was the most significant global health crisis since the Spanish Flu. Over 7 million confirmed deaths worldwide, with vaccines developed in record time. The pandemic transformed work, education, and social interaction.",[["2019-12","Cases emerge in Wuhan, China"],["2020-01-30","WHO declares emergency"],["2020-03-11","WHO declares pandemic"],["2020","Global lockdowns"],["2020-12","Vaccines authorized"],["2023-05-05","WHO ends emergency status"]]);
a("Chernobyl Disaster","1986-04-26","1986-04-26","Soviet Union",["Disaster","Nuclear Accident"],"The Chernobyl nuclear disaster on April 26, 1986, was the worst nuclear power plant accident in history. Reactor No. 4 exploded during a safety test, releasing radioactive contamination across Europe. 31 died immediately; long-term health effects affected millions.",[["1986-04-26","Reactor 4 explodes at 1:23 AM"],["1986-04-27","Pripyat evacuated"],["1986-05","Concrete sarcophagus construction"],["1986","Radioactive cloud reaches Western Europe"],["2000","Last reactor shut down"],["2016","New Safe Confinement completed"]]);
a("Fukushima Nuclear Disaster","2011-03-11","2011-03-11","Japan",["Disaster","Nuclear Accident"],"The Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster on March 11, 2011, was triggered by a massive earthquake and tsunami. Three reactor cores melted down, releasing radioactive material. It was the worst nuclear accident since Chernobyl and led to Japan's nuclear energy policy review.",[["2011-03-11","Magnitude 9.0 earthquake strikes"],["2011-03-11","14-meter tsunami hits plant"],["2011-03-12","Reactor 1 hydrogen explosion"],["2011-03-14","Reactor 3 explosion"],["2011-03-15","Reactor 2 and 4 damaged"],["2023","Treated water release begins"]]);
a("Great Kanto Earthquake","1923-09-01","1923-09-01","Japan",["Disaster","Natural Disaster"],"The Great Kantō Earthquake on September 1, 1923, devastated Tokyo and Yokohama with a magnitude 7.9 tremor. Fires destroyed most of Tokyo. Over 105,000 people died. The disaster led to major urban planning reforms and tragically sparked violence against Korean residents.",[["1923-09-01","Earthquake at 11:58 AM"],["1923-09-01","Massive fires erupt"],["1923","Tokyo and Yokohama devastated"],["1923","105,000+ dead"],["1923","Korean massacre amid chaos"],["1923","Reconstruction transforms Tokyo"]]);
a("Sinking of the Titanic","1912-04-14","1912-04-15","Atlantic Ocean",["Disaster","Maritime Disaster"],"The RMS Titanic sank on April 15, 1912, after striking an iceberg on its maiden voyage. Over 1,500 of the 2,224 passengers and crew died in the freezing North Atlantic. The 'unsinkable' ship's loss led to major improvements in maritime safety regulations.",[["1912-04-10","Titanic departs Southampton"],["1912-04-14","Iceberg struck at 11:40 PM"],["1912-04-15","Ship sinks at 2:20 AM"],["1912","1,500+ die"],["1912","Carpathia rescues 710 survivors"],["1914","SOLAS convention adopted"]]);
a("Hiroshima Atomic Bombing","1945-08-06","1945-08-06","Japan",["Disaster","Nuclear Attack"],"On August 6, 1945, the United States dropped the atomic bomb 'Little Boy' on Hiroshima, Japan. The explosion killed approximately 80,000 instantly and up to 140,000 by year's end. It was the first use of nuclear weapons in warfare.",[["1942","Manhattan Project begins"],["1945-07-16","Trinity test"],["1945-08-06","'Little Boy' dropped on Hiroshima"],["1945-08-06","80,000 killed instantly"],["1945-08-09","Nagasaki bombed"],["1945-08-15","Japan surrenders"]]);
a("Nagasaki Atomic Bombing","1945-08-09","1945-08-09","Japan",["Disaster","Nuclear Attack"],"On August 9, 1945, the United States dropped 'Fat Man' on Nagasaki, killing approximately 40,000 instantly and up to 80,000 by year's end. Combined with Hiroshima, the bombings forced Japan's surrender and ended World War II.",[["1945-08-06","Hiroshima bombed"],["1945-08-09","'Fat Man' dropped on Nagasaki"],["1945-08-09","40,000 killed instantly"],["1945-08-09","Kokura was original target"],["1945-08-15","Japan surrenders"],["1945","Nuclear age begins"]]);
a("Great Fire of London","1666-09-02","1666-09-05","England",["Disaster","Fire"],"The Great Fire of London from September 2-5, 1666, destroyed 13,200 houses and 87 churches, including St. Paul's Cathedral. The fire displaced 100,000 people but killed relatively few. It led to building regulations and Christopher Wren's reconstruction of London.",[["1665","Great Plague devastates London"],["1666-09-02","Fire starts in Pudding Lane bakery"],["1666-09-03","Fire spreads across city"],["1666-09-04","St. Paul's Cathedral burns"],["1666-09-05","Fire finally controlled"],["1675","New St. Paul's begun by Wren"]]);
a("Pompeii Eruption","0079-08-24","0079-08-25","Roman Empire",["Disaster","Volcanic Eruption"],"The eruption of Mount Vesuvius on August 24-25, 79 AD, buried the Roman cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum under volcanic ash. Thousands were killed. The preserved ruins provide an extraordinary snapshot of daily Roman life.",[["79-08-24","Vesuvius erupts"],["79-08-24","Pompeii buried in ash"],["79-08-25","Herculaneum buried in pyroclastic flows"],["79","Pliny the Elder dies observing"],["1748","Rediscovery of Pompeii"],["2024","Ongoing excavations"]]);
a("Krakatoa Eruption","1883-08-27","1883-08-27","Indonesia",["Disaster","Volcanic Eruption"],"The eruption of Krakatoa on August 27, 1883, was one of the most destructive volcanic events in recorded history. The explosion was heard 3,000 miles away and generated tsunamis killing 36,000 people. It lowered global temperatures and produced vivid sunsets for years.",[["1883-05","Activity begins"],["1883-08-26","Major eruptions begin"],["1883-08-27","Cataclysmic explosion"],["1883","Explosion heard 3,000 miles away"],["1883","36,000 killed by tsunamis"],["1883","Global temperatures drop"]]);
a("2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami","2004-12-26","2004-12-26","Indian Ocean",["Disaster","Natural Disaster"],"The 2004 Indian Ocean Tsunami, triggered by a magnitude 9.1 earthquake, killed approximately 230,000 people across 14 countries. It was one of the deadliest natural disasters in recorded history and led to the creation of Indian Ocean tsunami warning systems.",[["2004-12-26","Magnitude 9.1 earthquake off Sumatra"],["2004-12-26","Tsunami waves up to 30 meters"],["2004","Indonesia, Sri Lanka, India hardest hit"],["2004","230,000 killed"],["2004","Massive international aid response"],["2005","Tsunami warning systems established"]]);
a("Great Chinese Famine","1959-01-01","1961-12-31","China",["Disaster","Famine"],"The Great Chinese Famine (1959-1961) was the deadliest famine in human history, killing an estimated 15-55 million people. Caused by Mao Zedong's Great Leap Forward policies, including forced collectivization and unrealistic production quotas.",[["1958","Great Leap Forward begins"],["1959","Crop failures; famine begins"],["1960","Peak mortality"],["1961","Policies partially reversed"],["1961","Death toll: 15-55 million estimated"],["1962","Great Leap Forward abandoned"]]);
a("2011 Tohoku Earthquake and Tsunami","2011-03-11","2011-03-11","Japan",["Disaster","Natural Disaster"],"The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami was a magnitude 9.0 earthquake off Japan's coast. The resulting tsunami killed nearly 20,000 people and triggered the Fukushima nuclear disaster. It was the most powerful earthquake recorded in Japan.",[["2011-03-11","Magnitude 9.0 earthquake at 2:46 PM"],["2011-03-11","Tsunami waves devastate coast"],["2011-03-11","Fukushima reactors damaged"],["2011","Nearly 20,000 dead or missing"],["2011","$235 billion in damage"],["2011","Japan's nuclear policy changed"]]);
a("Great Irish Famine","1845-09-01","1852-01-01","Ireland",["Disaster","Famine"],"The Great Irish Famine (1845-1852) was caused by potato blight and exacerbated by British policies. Approximately 1 million died and another million emigrated. The famine halved Ireland's population and permanently altered Irish society and diaspora.",[["1845","Potato blight arrives"],["1846","Widespread crop failure"],["1847","Black '47: peak mortality"],["1848","Young Ireland rebellion"],["1849","Famine continues"],["1852","1 million dead; 1 million emigrated"]]);
a("Bhopal Gas Tragedy","1984-12-03","1984-12-03","India",["Disaster","Industrial Accident"],"The Bhopal gas tragedy on December 3, 1984, was the world's worst industrial disaster. A gas leak from a Union Carbide pesticide plant killed at least 3,800 immediately and up to 16,000 overall. Over 500,000 were exposed to toxic gases.",[["1984-12-02","Safety systems not functioning"],["1984-12-03","Methyl isocyanate gas leaks"],["1984-12-03","3,800 killed immediately"],["1984","500,000 exposed"],["1989","Union Carbide pays $470 million"],["2024","Health effects continue"]]);
a("Lisbon Earthquake","1755-11-01","1755-11-01","Portugal",["Disaster","Natural Disaster"],"The Lisbon earthquake on November 1, 1755, struck on All Saints' Day. The earthquake, fires, and tsunami destroyed most of Lisbon and killed 30,000-50,000. It profoundly influenced Enlightenment philosophy and seismology.",[["1755-11-01","Earthquake strikes at 9:40 AM"],["1755-11-01","Fires erupt across city"],["1755-11-01","Tsunami devastates harbor"],["1755","30,000-50,000 killed"],["1755","Pombal directs reconstruction"],["1755","Voltaire writes about disaster"]]);
a("Challenger Disaster","1986-01-28","1986-01-28","United States",["Disaster","Space Disaster"],"The Space Shuttle Challenger broke apart 73 seconds after launch on January 28, 1986, killing all seven crew members including teacher Christa McAuliffe. An O-ring failure in cold weather was the cause. The disaster led to major NASA safety reforms.",[["1986-01-28","Challenger launches in cold weather"],["1986-01-28","O-ring fails at 73 seconds"],["1986-01-28","Seven crew members killed"],["1986","Rogers Commission investigation"],["1986","O-ring failure identified"],["1988","Shuttle flights resume"]]);
a("Chernobyl Exclusion Zone","1986-04-27","1986-05-06","Soviet Union",["Disaster","Evacuation"],"The evacuation of the Chernobyl exclusion zone began April 27, 1986, when 49,000 residents of Pripyat were relocated within hours. Eventually 350,000 people were permanently resettled. The 30-km zone remains largely uninhabited and has become an accidental wildlife sanctuary.",[["1986-04-27","Pripyat evacuated"],["1986-05","30-km exclusion zone established"],["1986","116,000 relocated immediately"],["1990","Additional 220,000 relocated"],["2016","New Safe Confinement completed"],["2024","Zone remains restricted"]]);
a("Haiti Earthquake 2010","2010-01-12","2010-01-12","Haiti",["Disaster","Natural Disaster"],"The 2010 Haiti earthquake, a magnitude 7.0 tremor, struck near Port-au-Prince on January 12. It killed an estimated 100,000-316,000 people and displaced 1.5 million. Haiti's poverty and poor infrastructure compounded the devastation.",[["2010-01-12","Magnitude 7.0 earthquake"],["2010","Port-au-Prince devastated"],["2010","100,000-316,000 killed"],["2010","1.5 million displaced"],["2010","International aid mobilized"],["2010","Cholera outbreak follows"]]);

// ============ EMPIRES & DYNASTIES (~150) ============
a("Founding of Rome","0753-04-21","0753-04-21","Italy",["Empire","Ancient History"],"According to tradition, Rome was founded on April 21, 753 BC by Romulus, who became its first king. From these legendary beginnings grew the Roman Republic and later the Roman Empire, one of history's most influential civilizations.",[["753 BC","Romulus founds Rome (traditional)"],["509 BC","Roman Republic established"],["264 BC","Punic Wars begin"],["27 BC","Roman Empire begins under Augustus"],["117 AD","Empire at greatest extent"],["476 AD","Western Empire falls"]]);
a("Fall of the Western Roman Empire","0476-09-04","0476-09-04","Italy",["Empire","Ancient History"],"The fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 AD, when Germanic chieftain Odoacer deposed the last emperor Romulus Augustulus, traditionally marks the end of antiquity and the beginning of the Middle Ages in Europe.",[["395","Empire permanently divided"],["410","Visigoths sack Rome"],["455","Vandals sack Rome"],["476-09-04","Romulus Augustulus deposed"],["476","Western Empire ends"],["476","Middle Ages begin"]]);
a("Qin Unification of China","0221-01-01","0221-01-01","China",["Empire","Ancient History"],"In 221 BC, Qin Shi Huang unified China for the first time, establishing the Qin dynasty. He standardized weights, measures, writing, and currency, built the Great Wall's earliest sections, and created a centralized bureaucratic state that influenced China for millennia.",[["230 BC","Qin begins conquest of rival states"],["221 BC","Last rival state falls; China unified"],["221 BC","Qin Shi Huang declares himself First Emperor"],["214 BC","Great Wall construction begins"],["213 BC","Burning of books and burying of scholars"],["210 BC","Qin Shi Huang dies"]]);
a("Mongol Empire Formation","1206-01-01","1206-01-01","Mongolia",["Empire","Medieval History"],"In 1206, Temüjin was proclaimed Genghis Khan (Universal Ruler) at a great assembly, uniting the Mongol tribes. He built the largest contiguous land empire in history, stretching from Korea to Eastern Europe, through military brilliance and ruthless efficiency.",[["1162","Temüjin born"],["1206","Proclaimed Genghis Khan"],["1211","Invasion of Jin China"],["1219","Invasion of Khwarezmia"],["1227","Genghis Khan dies"],["1279","Empire at greatest extent"]]);
a("Ottoman Conquest of Constantinople","1453-05-29","1453-05-29","Turkey",["Empire","Medieval History"],"The Ottoman conquest of Constantinople on May 29, 1453, ended the Byzantine Empire and established the Ottomans as a major world power. Sultan Mehmed II renamed the city Istanbul and made it the Ottoman capital for nearly 500 years.",[["1453-04-06","Siege begins"],["1453-05-29","City falls"],["1453","Constantine XI killed"],["1453","Hagia Sophia converted to mosque"],["1453","City renamed Istanbul"],["1922","Ottoman Empire dissolved"]]);
a("Joseon Dynasty Founding","1392-07-17","1392-07-17","Korea",["Empire","Korean History"],"The Joseon dynasty was founded on July 17, 1392, by General Yi Seong-gye (King Taejo) after overthrowing the Goryeo dynasty. Joseon ruled Korea for over 500 years, adopting Confucianism, creating Hangul, and shaping Korean culture profoundly.",[["1388","Yi Seong-gye turns army at Wihwa Island"],["1392-07-17","Joseon dynasty founded"],["1394","Capital moved to Seoul"],["1443","King Sejong creates Hangul"],["1592","Japanese invasions begin"],["1897","Korean Empire proclaimed"]]);
a("End of Joseon Dynasty","1897-10-12","1910-08-29","Korea",["Empire","Korean History"],"The Joseon dynasty ended when Japan formally annexed Korea on August 29, 1910, ending the brief Korean Empire (1897-1910). The annexation followed decades of Japanese encroachment and ended 518 years of Korean self-rule.",[["1897","Korean Empire proclaimed"],["1905","Eulsa Treaty; Japanese protectorate"],["1907","Emperor Gojong forced to abdicate"],["1909","An Jung-geun assassinates Itō"],["1910-08-29","Japan annexes Korea"],["1945","Korea liberated from Japan"]]);
a("Meiji Restoration Japan","1868-01-03","1868-01-03","Japan",["Empire","Japanese History"],"The Meiji Restoration of 1868 ended 265 years of Tokugawa shogunate rule, restoring power to Emperor Meiji. Japan rapidly modernized through industrialization, Western-style institutions, and military reforms, becoming a major world power within decades.",[["1853","Perry's Black Ships arrive"],["1867","Last shogun resigns"],["1868-01-03","Restoration declared"],["1868","Boshin War"],["1889","Meiji Constitution"],["1905","Japan defeats Russia"]]);
a("Fall of the Qing Dynasty","1912-02-12","1912-02-12","China",["Empire","Chinese History"],"The Qing dynasty fell on February 12, 1912, when the six-year-old Emperor Puyi abdicated, ending over 2,000 years of imperial rule in China. The Xinhai Revolution of 1911 had already established the Republic of China.",[["1839","Opium Wars weaken Qing"],["1900","Boxer Rebellion"],["1905","Examination system abolished"],["1911-10-10","Wuchang Uprising"],["1912-01-01","Republic proclaimed"],["1912-02-12","Puyi abdicates"]]);
a("Dissolution of the Soviet Union","1991-12-26","1991-12-26","Soviet Union",["Empire","Cold War"],"The Soviet Union officially dissolved on December 26, 1991, ending the Cold War. Gorbachev's reforms, economic crisis, and nationalist movements in constituent republics led to the world's largest country breaking into 15 independent states.",[["1985","Gorbachev begins reforms"],["1989","Eastern Bloc collapses"],["1990","Baltic states declare independence"],["1991-08","Failed coup attempt"],["1991-12-08","Belavezha Accords"],["1991-12-26","Soviet Union dissolved"]]);
a("British Raj Begins","1858-11-01","1858-11-01","India",["Empire","Colonial History"],"The British Raj began on November 1, 1858, when the British Crown assumed direct control of India from the East India Company after the 1857 rebellion. The Raj lasted until 1947 and profoundly shaped the Indian subcontinent.",[["1757","Plassey; Company rule begins"],["1857","Indian Rebellion"],["1858-11-01","Government of India Act"],["1858","Crown takes control"],["1919","Jallianwala Bagh massacre"],["1947","Indian independence"]]);
a("Partition of India","1947-08-15","1947-08-15","India",["Empire","Decolonization"],"The Partition of India on August 15, 1947, created the independent nations of India and Pakistan. The hurried division along religious lines triggered massive population transfers and communal violence that killed 1-2 million people and displaced 15 million.",[["1940","Muslim League demands Pakistan"],["1946","Communal violence escalates"],["1947-06","Mountbatten Plan announced"],["1947-08-14","Pakistan created"],["1947-08-15","Indian independence"],["1947","1-2 million killed in violence"]]);
a("Goryeo Dynasty Founding","0918-06-15","0918-06-15","Korea",["Empire","Korean History"],"The Goryeo dynasty was founded in 918 by Wang Geon, who unified the Later Three Kingdoms of Korea by 936. Goryeo gave Korea its modern English name and was known for celadon pottery, Buddhist culture, and the invention of metal movable type.",[["918","Wang Geon founds Goryeo"],["935","Silla surrenders"],["936","Later Baekje conquered; unification"],["1234","Metal movable type invented"],["1270","Mongol invasions"],["1392","Joseon dynasty replaces Goryeo"]]);
a("Roman Republic Establishment","0509-01-01","0509-01-01","Italy",["Empire","Ancient History"],"The Roman Republic was established around 509 BC when the Romans overthrew their Etruscan king, Tarquinius Superbus. The Republic's system of elected magistrates, Senate, and popular assemblies became a model for democratic governance that influenced modern constitutions.",[["753 BC","Rome founded (traditional)"],["509 BC","Republic established"],["390 BC","Gauls sack Rome"],["264 BC","First Punic War"],["44 BC","Caesar assassinated"],["27 BC","Republic ends; Empire begins"]]);
a("Alexander the Great Empire","0336-01-01","0323-06-13","Macedonia",["Empire","Ancient History"],"Alexander the Great's empire (336-323 BC) stretched from Greece to northwestern India, the largest empire the world had yet seen. His conquests spread Greek culture (Hellenism) across the ancient world and founded over 20 cities, including Alexandria in Egypt.",[["336 BC","Alexander becomes king"],["334 BC","Invasion of Persia"],["331 BC","Battle of Gaugamela"],["327 BC","Invasion of India"],["323 BC","Alexander dies in Babylon"],["323 BC","Empire divided among successors"]]);
a("Ottoman Empire Dissolution","1922-11-01","1922-11-01","Turkey",["Empire","Modern History"],"The Ottoman Empire was formally abolished on November 1, 1922, when the Turkish Grand National Assembly ended the sultanate. After 623 years, one of history's longest-lasting empires gave way to the Republic of Turkey under Mustafa Kemal Atatürk.",[["1918","Ottoman defeat in WWI"],["1919","Turkish War of Independence begins"],["1920","Treaty of Sèvres imposed"],["1922","Turkey defeats Greece"],["1922-11-01","Sultanate abolished"],["1923","Republic of Turkey proclaimed"]]);
a("Holy Roman Empire Dissolution","1806-08-06","1806-08-06","Europe",["Empire","Modern History"],"The Holy Roman Empire was dissolved on August 6, 1806, when Emperor Francis II abdicated under pressure from Napoleon after the Battle of Austerlitz. The empire, which Voltaire quipped was 'neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire,' had existed for over 800 years.",[["962","Otto I crowned first Emperor"],["1648","Westphalia weakens Empire"],["1789","French Revolution begins"],["1805","Austerlitz; Napoleon triumphant"],["1806-08-06","Francis II abdicates"],["1806","800+ year empire ends"]]);
a("Founding of Goguryeo","0037-01-01","0037-01-01","Korea",["Empire","Korean History"],"Goguryeo was traditionally founded in 37 BC by Jumong. It became one of the Three Kingdoms of Korea and at its height controlled much of Manchuria and the Korean Peninsula. Known for its military prowess and distinctive tomb murals.",[["37 BC","Jumong founds Goguryeo"],["194","Capital moved to Gungnae"],["427","Capital moved to Pyongyang"],["612","Defeats Sui China invasion"],["645","Resists Tang China invasion"],["668","Falls to Silla-Tang alliance"]]);
a("Silla Unification of Korea","0668-01-01","0676-01-01","Korea",["Empire","Korean History"],"Silla's unification of the Korean Peninsula from 668-676 AD created the first unified Korean state. Allied with Tang China, Silla defeated Goguryeo and Baekje, then expelled Tang forces to maintain Korean independence.",[["660","Silla-Tang alliance defeats Baekje"],["668","Goguryeo falls"],["670","Silla resists Tang occupation"],["676","Tang forces expelled; unification complete"],["682","National Confucian Academy established"],["935","Silla surrenders to Goryeo"]]);

// ============ ECONOMIC & FINANCIAL (~150) ============
a("Great Depression","1929-10-29","1939-01-01","Global",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The Great Depression, triggered by the 1929 stock market crash, was the worst economic downturn in modern history. Global GDP fell 15%, unemployment reached 25% in the US, and the crisis contributed to the rise of fascism and World War II.",[["1929-10-24","Black Thursday crash"],["1929-10-29","Black Tuesday; market collapses"],["1930","Bank failures begin"],["1932","Unemployment peaks at 25%"],["1933","Roosevelt's New Deal"],["1939","WWII ends depression"]]);
a("Wall Street Crash 1929","1929-10-24","1929-10-29","United States",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The Wall Street Crash of October 1929 was the most devastating stock market collapse in American history. Black Thursday and Black Tuesday wiped out millions of investors and triggered the Great Depression.",[["1928","Speculative bubble grows"],["1929-10-24","Black Thursday"],["1929-10-28","Black Monday"],["1929-10-29","Black Tuesday; 16 million shares traded"],["1929","$30 billion lost"],["1930","Great Depression begins"]]);
a("South Sea Bubble","1720-01-01","1720-09-01","England",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The South Sea Bubble of 1720 was one of history's first major financial crashes. The South Sea Company's stock rose 800% on speculation before collapsing, ruining thousands of investors including Isaac Newton. It led to Britain's first financial regulation.",[["1711","South Sea Company founded"],["1720-01","Stock begins dramatic rise"],["1720-06","Stock peaks at £1,000"],["1720-09","Bubble bursts; stock collapses"],["1720","Newton loses £20,000"],["1720","Bubble Act passed"]]);
a("Tulip Mania","1636-11-01","1637-02-01","Netherlands",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"Tulip Mania (1636-37) was the first recorded speculative bubble. Dutch tulip bulb prices rose extraordinarily before collapsing in February 1637. A single bulb once sold for more than a house. It remains the classic example of irrational market exuberance.",[["1593","Tulips introduced to Netherlands"],["1634","Tulip speculation begins"],["1636","Futures trading in bulbs"],["1637-02","Prices crash overnight"],["1637","Many investors ruined"],["1637","First recorded financial bubble"]]);
a("2008 Global Financial Crisis","2007-08-09","2009-06-01","Global",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The 2008 financial crisis was the worst global economic disaster since the Great Depression. Triggered by the US subprime mortgage collapse and Lehman Brothers' failure, it caused worldwide recession, bank bailouts, and lasting economic reforms.",[["2007-08","Credit crisis begins"],["2008-03","Bear Stearns rescued"],["2008-09-15","Lehman Brothers collapses"],["2008-10","Global stock markets crash"],["2008","$700 billion TARP bailout"],["2009","Global recession"]]);
a("Asian Financial Crisis","1997-07-02","1998-12-01","East Asia",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The Asian Financial Crisis of 1997-98 devastated East Asian economies. Starting with Thailand's baht devaluation, the crisis spread to Indonesia, South Korea, and beyond. The IMF provided $118 billion in bailouts, reshaping Asian economic policies.",[["1997-07-02","Thai baht floated; collapses"],["1997-08","Indonesia crisis"],["1997-10","Hong Kong stock crash"],["1997-11","South Korea seeks IMF bailout"],["1998","Indonesian political crisis; Suharto falls"],["1999","Recovery begins"]]);
a("Nixon Shock","1971-08-15","1971-08-15","United States",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"Nixon Shock on August 15, 1971, was President Nixon's unilateral cancellation of the dollar's convertibility to gold, effectively ending the Bretton Woods system. The move fundamentally changed the global monetary system to floating exchange rates.",[["1944","Bretton Woods established"],["1960s","Dollar overvaluation grows"],["1971-08-15","Nixon suspends gold convertibility"],["1971","Wage and price controls imposed"],["1973","Floating exchange rates begin"],["1971","Bretton Woods system ends"]]);
a("Oil Crisis 1973","1973-10-17","1974-03-18","Global",["Economic Crisis","Energy"],"The 1973 Oil Crisis began when OPEC proclaimed an oil embargo against nations supporting Israel during the Yom Kippur War. Oil prices quadrupled, causing global recession and long gas lines. It demonstrated the West's dependence on Middle Eastern oil.",[["1973-10-06","Yom Kippur War begins"],["1973-10-17","OPEC embargo announced"],["1973","Oil price quadruples"],["1974","Gas lines and rationing"],["1974-03","Embargo lifted"],["1973","West's oil dependence exposed"]]);
a("Oil Crisis 1979","1979-01-01","1980-01-01","Global",["Economic Crisis","Energy"],"The 1979 Oil Crisis was triggered by the Iranian Revolution's disruption of oil production. Oil prices more than doubled, causing global inflation and recession. It accelerated the shift toward energy conservation and alternative sources.",[["1979","Iranian Revolution disrupts oil"],["1979","Oil production drops 7%"],["1979","Oil prices more than double"],["1980","Iran-Iraq War further disrupts"],["1980","Global recession"],["1986","Oil prices crash"]]);
a("Dot-com Bubble Burst","2000-03-10","2002-10-09","United States",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The dot-com bubble burst in March 2000 when the NASDAQ peaked at 5,048 before crashing 78% by October 2002. Hundreds of internet companies failed, wiping out $5 trillion in market value. It ended the 1990s internet gold rush.",[["1995","Internet companies boom"],["1999","Irrational exuberance peaks"],["2000-03-10","NASDAQ peaks at 5,048"],["2000","Dot-com companies begin failing"],["2001","Recession"],["2002-10","NASDAQ bottoms at 1,114"]]);
a("IMF Crisis South Korea","1997-12-03","1998-12-31","South Korea",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"South Korea's 1997 IMF crisis was a national humiliation that required a $58 billion bailout. Citizens donated gold to help repay debts. The crisis restructured the chaebol-dominated economy and is seared into Korean national memory.",[["1997-10","Won begins rapid decline"],["1997-11","Korea applies for IMF assistance"],["1997-12-03","$58 billion bailout agreed"],["1998","Citizens donate gold"],["1998","Massive restructuring"],["2001","IMF loans fully repaid"]]);
a("Black Monday 1987","1987-10-19","1987-10-19","Global",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"Black Monday on October 19, 1987, saw the largest one-day percentage decline in stock market history. The Dow Jones fell 22.6% in a single day, with cascading crashes across global markets. The crisis led to the introduction of circuit breakers.",[["1987-10-19","Dow falls 22.6%"],["1987-10-19","$500 billion in value lost"],["1987","Global markets crash"],["1987","Fed provides liquidity"],["1988","Circuit breakers introduced"],["1988","Markets recover"]]);
a("European Debt Crisis","2009-12-01","2015-07-01","Europe",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The European Debt Crisis (2009-2015) threatened the eurozone when Greece, Ireland, Portugal, Spain, and Cyprus needed bailouts. It tested the EU's cohesion and led to austerity measures that caused widespread social unrest.",[["2009","Greece reveals massive deficit"],["2010","Greek bailout"],["2010","Ireland bailout"],["2011","Portugal bailout"],["2012","Draghi: 'whatever it takes'"],["2015","Greek crisis intensifies"]]);
a("Japanese Asset Bubble Burst","1991-01-01","1992-12-31","Japan",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"Japan's asset bubble burst in 1991 ended decades of rapid economic growth and ushered in the 'Lost Decade.' Real estate and stock prices collapsed by 80%. Japan has struggled with deflation and stagnation for over three decades since.",[["1985","Plaza Accord strengthens yen"],["1986-89","Asset prices soar"],["1989-12-29","Nikkei peaks at 38,957"],["1991","Bubble bursts; prices collapse"],["1992","Real estate values plummet"],["2000s","Lost Decades continue"]]);
a("Hyperinflation in Weimar Germany","1921-01-01","1923-11-15","Germany",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"Weimar Germany's hyperinflation (1921-1923) saw prices double every few days. A loaf of bread cost billions of marks. People burned currency for warmth. The crisis destroyed savings and contributed to political extremism and Hitler's rise.",[["1918","War reparations imposed"],["1921","Germany prints money to pay"],["1922","Inflation accelerates"],["1923-01","French occupy Ruhr"],["1923-11","One dollar = 4.2 trillion marks"],["1923-11-15","Rentenmark stabilizes currency"]]);
a("Argentine Economic Crisis","2001-12-01","2002-04-01","Argentina",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"Argentina's 2001 economic crisis saw the country default on $100 billion in debt, the largest sovereign default in history at that time. Bank accounts were frozen, five presidents served in two weeks, and half the population fell below the poverty line.",[["1991","Peso pegged to dollar"],["2001-12","Bank deposits frozen ('corralito')"],["2001-12-20","President de la Rúa resigns"],["2001","Five presidents in two weeks"],["2002","Peso devaluation"],["2002","Half population in poverty"]]);
a("South Sea Company Crash","1720-09-01","1720-09-01","England",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The South Sea Company crash of September 1720 was one of history's first major financial collapses. Share prices fell from £1,000 to under £100, ruining investors and triggering political scandal. Isaac Newton lost a fortune.",[["1711","Company founded"],["1720-01","Share price rises"],["1720-06","Peak at £1,000"],["1720-09","Crash begins"],["1720","Newton loses £20,000"],["1721","Bubble Act legislation"]]);
a("Mississippi Bubble","1718-01-01","1720-05-01","France",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The Mississippi Bubble (1718-1720) was a speculative mania surrounding John Law's Mississippi Company in France. When the bubble burst, it bankrupted France and destroyed public confidence in paper currency for generations.",[["1716","John Law establishes bank"],["1717","Mississippi Company formed"],["1719","Share price soars 2,000%"],["1720","Bubble bursts"],["1720","Law flees France"],["1720","French economy devastated"]]);
a("Panic of 1907","1907-10-01","1907-11-30","United States",["Economic Crisis","Financial"],"The Panic of 1907 was a US financial crisis in which the stock market fell 50% and numerous banks faced runs. J.P. Morgan personally organized a consortium of bankers to avert total collapse. The crisis led directly to the creation of the Federal Reserve.",[["1907-10","Stock market drops 50%"],["1907","Bank runs begin"],["1907","J.P. Morgan organizes bailout"],["1907","Trust companies fail"],["1910","Aldrich Plan proposed"],["1913","Federal Reserve created"]]);

// ============ SCIENCE & TECHNOLOGY (~100) ============
a("Industrial Revolution Begins","1760-01-01","1840-01-01","United Kingdom",["Science","Technology"],"The Industrial Revolution (1760-1840) transformed Britain from an agrarian society to an industrial power. Steam power, factory systems, and mechanization revolutionized manufacturing, transportation, and daily life, spreading globally and reshaping civilization.",[["1712","Newcomen steam engine"],["1764","Spinning jenny invented"],["1769","Watt improves steam engine"],["1771","First factory at Cromford"],["1825","First passenger railway"],["1840","Industrialization spreads globally"]]);
a("Invention of the Steam Engine","1712-01-01","1712-01-01","United Kingdom",["Science","Technology"],"Thomas Newcomen invented the first practical steam engine in 1712 to pump water from mines. James Watt later improved it dramatically, making it the driving force of the Industrial Revolution that transformed industry, transportation, and civilization.",[["1698","Savery's steam pump"],["1712","Newcomen engine"],["1769","Watt's separate condenser"],["1776","Watt engines in factories"],["1804","Steam locomotive"],["1825","First passenger railway"]]);
a("First Computer ENIAC","1945-11-01","1945-11-01","United States",["Science","Technology"],"ENIAC (Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer), completed in November 1945, was the first general-purpose electronic computer. Weighing 30 tons and filling a large room, it could perform 5,000 calculations per second—launching the computer age.",[["1943","ENIAC construction begins"],["1945-11","ENIAC completed"],["1946-02-14","Publicly unveiled"],["1945","30 tons; 18,000 vacuum tubes"],["1952","Used for hydrogen bomb calculations"],["1955","ENIAC decommissioned"]]);
a("World Wide Web Launch","1991-08-06","1991-08-06","Switzerland",["Science","Technology"],"Tim Berners-Lee publicly launched the World Wide Web on August 6, 1991, when the first website went live at CERN. His invention of HTML, URLs, and HTTP transformed the internet from an academic tool into a global information platform.",[["1989","Berners-Lee proposes the Web"],["1990","First web browser created"],["1991-08-06","First website goes live"],["1993","Mosaic browser; Web goes mainstream"],["1994","Amazon and Yahoo founded"],["2024","5+ billion web users"]]);
a("First iPhone Released","2007-06-29","2007-06-29","United States",["Science","Technology"],"Apple's iPhone, released June 29, 2007, revolutionized mobile technology by combining a phone, iPod, and internet device with a touchscreen interface. Steve Jobs's creation launched the smartphone era and transformed how billions interact with technology.",[["2007-01-09","Steve Jobs unveils iPhone"],["2007-06-29","iPhone goes on sale"],["2007","500,000 sold first weekend"],["2008","App Store launches"],["2007","Smartphone revolution begins"],["2024","Over 2 billion iPhones sold"]]);
a("Theory of Relativity Published","1905-06-30","1905-06-30","Switzerland",["Science","Physics"],"Albert Einstein published his Special Theory of Relativity in 1905, including E=mc². His 1915 General Theory of Relativity described gravity as spacetime curvature. These theories fundamentally changed our understanding of space, time, and the universe.",[["1905","Special Relativity published"],["1905","E=mc² formulated"],["1905","Miracle Year: four groundbreaking papers"],["1915","General Relativity published"],["1919","Eclipse confirms General Relativity"],["1921","Nobel Prize in Physics"]]);
a("First Nuclear Reactor Chicago Pile","1942-12-02","1942-12-02","United States",["Science","Nuclear Physics"],"Chicago Pile-1, the world's first nuclear reactor, achieved a self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction on December 2, 1942, under Enrico Fermi's direction. The experiment proved that nuclear energy could be harnessed, paving the way for both nuclear weapons and power.",[["1938","Nuclear fission discovered"],["1942","Manhattan Project begins"],["1942-12-02","Chicago Pile-1 goes critical"],["1942","Fermi: 'The Italian navigator has landed'"],["1945","Atomic bombs built"],["1951","First nuclear power electricity"]]);
a("First Satellite Television Broadcast","1962-07-23","1962-07-23","Global",["Science","Technology"],"The first live transatlantic television broadcast via the Telstar satellite on July 23, 1962, showed images from the US to Europe and back. It demonstrated satellite communication's potential and launched the era of global live television.",[["1957","Sputnik inspires satellite race"],["1962-07-10","Telstar 1 launched"],["1962-07-23","First live transatlantic TV broadcast"],["1962","Images transmitted US to Europe"],["1963","First geostationary satellite"],["1969","Moon landing broadcast globally"]]);
a("GPS System Operational","1995-04-27","1995-04-27","United States",["Science","Technology"],"The Global Positioning System (GPS) was declared fully operational on April 27, 1995. Originally a US military system, GPS was opened for civilian use and now provides location services for billions of devices worldwide.",[["1973","GPS program begins"],["1978","First GPS satellite launched"],["1983","Reagan opens GPS to civilians after KAL 007"],["1993","Initial operational capability"],["1995-04-27","Full operational capability"],["2000","Selective Availability removed"]]);
a("Human Cloning Dolly the Sheep","1996-07-05","1996-07-05","United Kingdom",["Science","Genetics"],"Dolly the Sheep, born July 5, 1996, was the first mammal cloned from an adult somatic cell. Created at the Roslin Institute in Scotland, Dolly sparked worldwide debate about cloning ethics and the future of genetic science.",[["1996-07-05","Dolly born at Roslin Institute"],["1997-02-22","Dolly announced to public"],["1997","Global cloning debate"],["1997","Many nations ban human cloning"],["2003","Dolly dies of lung disease"],["2024","Cloning technology advances"]]);
a("Discovery of Radioactivity","1896-03-01","1896-03-01","France",["Science","Physics"],"Henri Becquerel accidentally discovered radioactivity in March 1896 when he found that uranium salts emitted rays that could fog photographic plates. Marie and Pierre Curie furthered the research, discovering polonium and radium.",[["1895","Röntgen discovers X-rays"],["1896-03","Becquerel discovers radioactivity"],["1898","Curies discover polonium and radium"],["1903","Nobel Prize shared"],["1934","Marie Curie dies of radiation exposure"],["1942","First nuclear reactor"]]);
a("First Successful Heart Transplant","1967-12-03","1967-12-03","South Africa",["Science","Medicine"],"Dr. Christiaan Barnard performed the first successful human heart transplant on December 3, 1967, at Groote Schuur Hospital in Cape Town. Patient Louis Washkansky survived 18 days. The achievement opened the era of organ transplantation.",[["1960","First kidney transplant"],["1967-12-03","Barnard performs heart transplant"],["1967","Washkansky survives 18 days"],["1968","Second patient survives 19 months"],["1983","Cyclosporine improves survival"],["2024","Heart transplants routine"]]);

// ============ SOCIAL & CULTURAL (~150) ============
a("Protestant Reformation","1517-10-31","1517-10-31","Germany",["Social Movement","Religion"],"Martin Luther's posting of the 95 Theses on October 31, 1517, launched the Protestant Reformation. His challenge to papal authority and Catholic practices split Western Christianity, transforming European religion, politics, and culture.",[["1517-10-31","95 Theses posted at Wittenberg"],["1521","Diet of Worms; Luther excommunicated"],["1530","Augsburg Confession"],["1555","Peace of Augsburg"],["1536","Calvin in Geneva"],["1648","Westphalia ends religious wars"]]);
a("Abolition of Slavery in British Empire","1833-08-28","1833-08-28","United Kingdom",["Social Movement","Abolition"],"The Slavery Abolition Act of 1833 abolished slavery throughout most of the British Empire. Decades of abolitionist campaigning by William Wilberforce and others culminated in this landmark legislation, though the £20 million compensation went to slave owners, not the enslaved.",[["1787","Abolitionist movement begins"],["1807","Slave trade abolished"],["1831","Jamaican slave revolt"],["1833-08-28","Abolition Act passed"],["1834","Slavery formally ends"],["1838","'Apprenticeship' system ends"]]);
a("Emancipation Proclamation","1863-01-01","1863-01-01","United States",["Social Movement","Abolition"],"The Emancipation Proclamation, effective January 1, 1863, declared slaves in Confederate states to be free. While it didn't immediately free all slaves, it transformed the Civil War into a fight for human liberty and paved the way for the 13th Amendment.",[["1862-09-22","Preliminary proclamation after Antietam"],["1863-01-01","Proclamation takes effect"],["1863","180,000 Black soldiers join Union"],["1863","War becomes fight for freedom"],["1865","13th Amendment ratified"],["1865","Slavery abolished in US"]]);
a("Women's Suffrage Movement","1848-07-19","1920-08-18","United States",["Social Movement","Women's Rights"],"The American women's suffrage movement began with the Seneca Falls Convention in 1848 and culminated with the 19th Amendment in 1920. Decades of activism by Susan B. Anthony, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, and others won women the right to vote.",[["1848-07-19","Seneca Falls Convention"],["1869","Wyoming Territory grants women's suffrage"],["1913","Suffrage march in Washington"],["1917","Silent Sentinels picket White House"],["1919","19th Amendment passes Congress"],["1920-08-18","19th Amendment ratified"]]);
a("Civil Rights Act 1964","1964-07-02","1964-07-02","United States",["Social Movement","Civil Rights"],"The Civil Rights Act of 1964 was landmark legislation prohibiting discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, or national origin. It ended segregation in public places and banned employment discrimination, transforming American society.",[["1955","Montgomery Bus Boycott"],["1963","March on Washington; 'I Have a Dream'"],["1963","Kennedy proposes civil rights bill"],["1963-11","Johnson takes office; prioritizes bill"],["1964-07-02","Civil Rights Act signed"],["1965","Voting Rights Act follows"]]);
a("Fall of the Berlin Wall","1989-11-09","1989-11-09","Germany",["Social Movement","Cold War"],"The Berlin Wall fell on November 9, 1989, when East German authorities opened border checkpoints. Jubilant crowds tore down the wall, symbolizing the end of the Cold War and communist rule in Europe.",[["1961","Berlin Wall built"],["1989-09","Leipzig protests"],["1989-10","Honecker resigns"],["1989-11-09","Border opened"],["1989-11-09","Wall torn down"],["1990-10-03","Germany reunified"]]);
a("Nelson Mandela Release","1990-02-11","1990-02-11","South Africa",["Social Movement","Anti-Apartheid"],"Nelson Mandela was released from Victor Verster Prison on February 11, 1990, after 27 years of imprisonment. His release marked the beginning of the end of apartheid and South Africa's transition to democracy.",[["1962","Mandela arrested"],["1964","Sentenced to life imprisonment"],["1988","International pressure mounts"],["1990-02-02","De Klerk unbans ANC"],["1990-02-11","Mandela released"],["1994","Mandela elected president"]]);
a("Universal Declaration of Human Rights","1948-12-10","1948-12-10","Global",["Social Movement","International Law"],"The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted December 10, 1948, was the first global expression of fundamental human rights. Drafted under Eleanor Roosevelt's leadership, it has been translated into over 500 languages and inspired human rights movements worldwide.",[["1945","UN Charter signed"],["1946","Human Rights Commission formed"],["1947","Eleanor Roosevelt chairs drafting"],["1948-12-10","Declaration adopted"],["1948","30 articles of fundamental rights"],["2024","Foundation of human rights law"]]);
a("End of Apartheid","1994-04-27","1994-04-27","South Africa",["Social Movement","Anti-Apartheid"],"The end of apartheid culminated on April 27, 1994, when South Africa held its first fully democratic elections. Nelson Mandela was elected president, ending decades of racial segregation. The peaceful transition became a model of reconciliation.",[["1948","Apartheid policy begins"],["1960","Sharpeville massacre"],["1990","Mandela released"],["1991","Apartheid laws repealed"],["1994-04-27","First democratic elections"],["1994","Mandela elected president"]]);
a("March on Washington","1963-08-28","1963-08-28","United States",["Social Movement","Civil Rights"],"The March on Washington on August 28, 1963, drew over 250,000 people to the Lincoln Memorial. Martin Luther King Jr.'s 'I Have a Dream' speech became one of history's most iconic orations, building momentum for the Civil Rights Act.",[["1963-08-28","250,000 gather at Mall"],["1963-08-28","'I Have a Dream' speech"],["1963","Pressure on Kennedy for legislation"],["1964","Civil Rights Act passed"],["1965","Voting Rights Act"],["1968","King assassinated"]]);
a("Abolition of Serfdom Russia","1861-03-03","1861-03-03","Russia",["Social Movement","Reform"],"Tsar Alexander II's Emancipation Reform of 1861 freed Russia's 23 million serfs. Though the terms were often unfavorable to peasants, it was the most significant social reform in Russian history and contributed to modernization.",[["1855","Alexander II becomes Tsar"],["1856","Crimean War defeat spurs reform"],["1861-03-03","Emancipation Manifesto issued"],["1861","23 million serfs freed"],["1864","Zemstvo local government created"],["1881","Alexander II assassinated"]]);
a("Seneca Falls Convention","1848-07-19","1848-07-20","United States",["Social Movement","Women's Rights"],"The Seneca Falls Convention of July 19-20, 1848, was the first women's rights convention in the United States. The Declaration of Sentiments, modeled on the Declaration of Independence, declared that 'all men and women are created equal.'",[["1840","Women excluded from anti-slavery convention"],["1848-07-19","Convention opens at Seneca Falls"],["1848-07-19","Declaration of Sentiments presented"],["1848","68 women and 32 men sign"],["1851","Susan B. Anthony joins movement"],["1920","Women win the vote"]]);
a("Montgomery Bus Boycott","1955-12-01","1956-12-20","United States",["Social Movement","Civil Rights"],"The Montgomery Bus Boycott (1955-56), sparked by Rosa Parks' refusal to give up her seat, was a pivotal civil rights protest. For 381 days, Black residents boycotted city buses, ultimately winning a Supreme Court ruling desegregating buses.",[["1955-12-01","Rosa Parks arrested"],["1955-12-05","Boycott begins; King leads"],["1956","Black residents walk and carpool"],["1956-06","Federal court rules segregation unconstitutional"],["1956-11","Supreme Court affirms"],["1956-12-20","Buses desegregated"]]);
a("Indian Independence","1947-08-15","1947-08-15","India",["Social Movement","Independence"],"India gained independence from British rule on August 15, 1947, culminating decades of struggle led by Gandhi, Nehru, and others. The non-violent movement became a model for independence movements worldwide, though partition brought tragic violence.",[["1919","Jallianwala Bagh massacre"],["1920","Gandhi's non-cooperation movement"],["1930","Salt March"],["1942","Quit India Movement"],["1947-08-15","Independence Day"],["1947","Partition and violence"]]);
a("Abolition of Atlantic Slave Trade","1807-03-25","1807-03-25","United Kingdom",["Social Movement","Abolition"],"The Slave Trade Act of 1807 abolished the slave trade in the British Empire. The culmination of William Wilberforce's 20-year campaign, it was a landmark in human rights history, though slavery itself continued until 1833.",[["1787","Committee for Abolition formed"],["1789","Wilberforce's first abolition speech"],["1791","Haitian Revolution begins"],["1807-03-25","Slave Trade Act passed"],["1807","British Navy enforces ban"],["1833","Slavery itself abolished"]]);
a("Declaration of Independence","1776-07-04","1776-07-04","United States",["Social Movement","Independence"],"The Declaration of Independence, adopted July 4, 1776, proclaimed the thirteen colonies' independence from Britain. Drafted primarily by Thomas Jefferson, its assertion that 'all men are created equal' became a foundational statement of human rights.",[["1775","Revolutionary War begins"],["1776-01","Paine's Common Sense"],["1776-06","Committee appointed"],["1776-07-02","Independence voted"],["1776-07-04","Declaration adopted"],["1776","56 delegates sign"]]);

// ============ KOREAN HISTORY (~200) ============
a("Gojoseon Foundation","2333-10-03","2333-10-03","Korea",["Empire","Korean History"],"According to Korean tradition, Gojoseon was founded by Dangun on October 3, 2333 BC, making it the first Korean kingdom. The founding myth connects the Korean people to a divine origin and is commemorated annually as National Foundation Day.",[["2333 BC","Dangun founds Gojoseon (traditional)"],["108 BC","Han China destroys Gojoseon"],["4th c. BC","Historical records of Gojoseon"],["194 BC","Wiman takes power"],["108 BC","Gojoseon falls"],["2024","National Foundation Day celebrated"]]);
a("Imjin War Japanese Invasion","1592-04-13","1598-12-16","Korea",["War","Korean History"],"The Imjin War (1592-1598) was Japan's invasion of Korea under Toyotomi Hideyoshi. Initial Japanese success was reversed by Admiral Yi Sun-sin's naval victories and Ming Chinese intervention. The war devastated Korea but failed to achieve Japanese objectives.",[["1592-04-13","Japanese land at Busan"],["1592-06","Seoul falls"],["1592-08","Yi Sun-sin's naval victories"],["1593","Ming Chinese intervention"],["1597","Second invasion"],["1598","Hideyoshi dies; Japanese withdraw"]]);
a("Byeongja Horan","1636-12-01","1637-01-30","Korea",["War","Korean History"],"The Manchu invasion of Korea (Byeongja Horan) in 1636-37 forced Joseon to submit to the Qing dynasty. King Injo surrendered at Namhansanseong fortress, and Korea became a Qing tributary. The humiliation deeply scarred Korean national consciousness.",[["1627","First Manchu invasion (Jeongmyo)"],["1636-12","Manchu army invades Korea"],["1637-01","King Injo retreats to Namhansanseong"],["1637-01-30","King Injo surrenders"],["1637","Korea becomes Qing tributary"],["1637","Crown princes taken hostage"]]);
a("Gabo Reform","1894-07-27","1896-02-11","Korea",["Reform","Korean History"],"The Gabo Reforms of 1894-1896 were a series of sweeping modernization measures in Joseon Korea. They abolished the class system, reformed government, banned child marriage, and introduced Western-style institutions. The reforms were Korea's first major attempt at modernization.",[["1894","Donghak Peasant Revolution"],["1894-07-27","First reform cabinet"],["1894","Class system abolished"],["1894","Civil service exams reformed"],["1895","Lunar calendar replaced"],["1896","Reforms slow after Empress murder"]]);
a("Eulsa Treaty","1905-11-17","1905-11-17","Korea",["Treaty","Korean History"],"The Eulsa Treaty (Japan-Korea Protectorate Treaty) of November 17, 1905, stripped Korea of its diplomatic sovereignty, making it a Japanese protectorate. The treaty was signed under military coercion, and five Korean ministers who signed became known as the 'Eulsa Five Traitors.'",[["1904","Japan-Korea Protocol"],["1905","Japan wins Russo-Japanese War"],["1905-11-17","Treaty signed under coercion"],["1905","Korean diplomatic sovereignty lost"],["1907","Emperor Gojong sends envoys to Hague"],["1910","Japan fully annexes Korea"]]);
a("March 1st Movement 1919","1919-03-01","1919-05-01","Korea",["Revolution","Independence Movement"],"The March 1st Movement of 1919 was Korea's largest independence demonstration against Japanese colonial rule. Over 2 million Koreans participated in peaceful protests nationwide. Brutal Japanese suppression killed thousands but galvanized Korean nationalism.",[["1919-03-01","Independence Declaration read"],["1919-03","Protests spread nationwide"],["1919","2 million+ participate"],["1919","Japanese kill thousands"],["1919-04","Provisional Government in Shanghai"],["1945","Korea finally liberated"]]);
